        7 July 2023 - 13 July 2023

        The Official Singles Chart Top 100 reflects the UKs biggest songs of the week, based on audio and video streams, downloads, CDs and vinyl, compiled by the Official Charts Company. The UK Top 40 is broadcast on BBC Radio 1. View the biggest songs of 2025.

        Chart Review 07/07/2023

        Alright let's get this over with.

        Welcome to another (hopefully longer) edition of the annual chart reviews I do now, where logic burns to smithereens, and the songs will NEVER. EVER. LEAVE. This time around, it's more of the same, as expected. Honestly, the day there's like 10 new entries that aren't Christmas related is the day I run for prime minister. Obviously, that's never gonna happen, even though I'd probably do better than the wimps that ARE in charge. A little optimism never killed anyone.

        Just 3 new hits which seems par for the course these days, as Dave and Central Cee casually put some lounge chairs up and sip some Coca-Cola, asSprintermakes it a fifth week at the top. Apparently it ties for the longest running UK rap #1, along with... Dave. Naturally. It's almost like everybody likes Dave, no matter what he does. He's like the Ed Sheeran of UK Rap (which is down 6 to 25, if you were wondering).

        This naturally means that everybody has to gasp in horror at the sight of Olivia Rodrigo NOT debuting at No.1 withvampire. Olivia (or O-Rod as I like to call her) is usually mocked for making way too manydriver's licenseclones, which is a bit unfair, but this is what happens in the 2020s. TikTok rules all, so deal with it. Anyways, O-Rod's second album is out in September, and here comes the first huge hit off it.vampiredidn't impress me at first (what does), mainly because I barely heard it on the radio (in full anyway), but once I got submerged by all those LAUD DRUMZ near the end, it's slightly grew. Slightly. Still, this is a bit of a disappointment to see O-Rod at No.2. Not even the DREADED PHYSICAL RELEASE was enough to get her there, which is a bit worrying. However,good 4 udebuted at 2 before powering past all-comers, so don't lose faith yet folks (6.6/10).

        Taylor Swift keeps dragging herself up the chart, withCruel Summernow at 6. Her attempts to rerecord everything she was ever a part of continues withSpeak Now (Taylor's Version), although I'm just waiting for the bit where she remakes her remake albums to REALLY test the average fans patience. As if it wasn't hard enough to get those tour tickets.

        Meanwhile at 10, the world shrieks and snoozes in equal measure as D-Block Europe get what is only their 3rd Top 10 hit withPakistan, out of 25 top 40 showings. You don't need to be a rocket scientist to guess what THIS one sounds like, as you can predict the Young Adz-Lamborghini-girlfriend-alcohol malarkey before they happen. Their albumDBE Worldalso dropped today. What do you mean you didn't notice? (3.2/10)

        Oh, and after what feels like forever (5 weeks, actually, which isn't that long), British producer and lame dance DJ of the Joel Corry variety D.O.D. crawls his way to 38 withSo Much In Love. He is best known forStill Sleeplesswhich spent, oh, I don't know, TWENTY-ONE WEEKS in the charts and didn't get higher than 46. So at lest he's trying I suppose. Doesn't mean the song is any good (4.8/10).

        Over on thy album chart, thou shalt honour indie group Nothing But Thieves, whose previous showings are 7, 2, and 3, but now have a 1 to add to this collection, in the form of Dead Club City. They're from Southend-on-Sea don't cha know. Stuck playing the roles of "we are also in the top 10, but will hopefully not be in the top 100 next week" are Olivia Dean with her debut albumMessy, Lil Uzi Vert, whose new collection is calledPink Tape, and Fontaines D.C. lead singer Grian Chatten whose solo album goes by the nameChaos for the Fly. You won't buy any of these next week, obviously, but they are here for you to mingle with.

        In the top 100 singles chart stakes, and ANOTR STILL CAN'T BUY A TOP 40 PLACING TO SAVE HIS LIFE, and Fall Out Boy stumble to 52 on the chart with their "timely" cover of Billy Joel'sWe Didn't Start The Fire. Naturally. First band I think of. I would've loved it if they cracked the 40 but nope! Guess I'll have to cry in my 2007 merchandise like a true emo instead. Also, the album chart has Japanese House, The Skids, bdrmm, Lucinda Williams, Stone Foundation, Do Nothing, and Jim Bob on it. And yet they'll all be outsold next week by Pitbull's Greatest Hits. Lord have mercy on us.

        But yeah, that is that for another week. Hopefully, some stuff will happen the next time I grasp this commenting section in 7 days' time, but for now, I will have to hibernate in my own sorrow. Cheerio.


        (P.S. Oh, and The Killers'Mr. Brightsidehas now spent a total of 369 weeks on the chart. Just wanted to let you know, 'cause it is cool and all.)

        (P.P.S. I also forgot to mention Charli XCX messing up with her Barbie soundtrack contribution. But it's not like it matters or anything. And also, SWITCH DISCO ARE OUT THE TOP 10. FINALLY. IT'S LIKE A MIRACLE HAS HAPPENED OR SOMETHING.)
